stimulus:
Before we begin the main task, you will complete a short volume calibration and headphone check.

Please make sure you are in a quiet listening environment, that you are wearing headphones, and that your computer's volume is turned on.

The volume calibration will be first.

You will hear a thirty-second noise. Please adjust your computer's volume so that this noise is being presented at a comfortable level.

You will now complete a short headphone check.

On each trial, you will hear three tones. One of these tones will be quieter than the others. Your task is to identify whether the quiet tone occurred first, second, or third.

There are six trials in total.

(Press SPACEBAR to begin)

There are two blocks to this experiment.

In each block, you will hear a ~13.5 minute story. One of the stories will be scrambled. Please listen carefully to both stories and understand them as best you can.

After each story, you will be asked some questions to assess your comprehension.

During each story, there will be an additional task.

A letter will occasionally appear on the screen.
Your job is to - as quickly as you can - decide whether the letter is lowercase or uppercase and press one of two keys on the keyboard:

If the letter is lowercase, press key <x>.

If the letter is uppercase, press key <m>.

Because we want your responses to be as quick as possible, please keep your index fingers over the keys while listening.

Each block lasts about 20 minutes.

Press <x> or <m> to start the first block!

This concludes the story. Thank you for listening.

You will now answer some questions about the content of the story.
How did the dogs respond when they saw the bears?
What was the objective of the narrator's expedition?
How did the narrator's encounter with the polar bears end?
responses: {"Q0":"The bears walked back to their den."}

stimulus: What did the narrator do for leisure while in her tent?
What is the name of the narrator's neighbour?
How many sponsorships did the narrator receive to support her expedition?
Which dog on the narrator's dog team never followed instructions?
How did the narrator's neighbour respond when she told him about her expedition?
responses: {"Q0":"He said he was worried about her."}

stimulus: What were the weather conditions in the Arctic like the winter of the narrator's expedition?
responses: {"Q0":"There were more storms than any other winter in recorded history."}

stimulus: How did the narrator prepare for her expedition?
responses: {"Q0":"Trained in Alaska learning how to dogsled"}

stimulus:
Thank you for your responses.

You will now answer some questions about your impressions of the story.

Thank you for your responses. You will now listen to the second story.

Remember, as you listen to the story you will see letters appear on the screen.
As quickly as possible, press <x> if the letter is lowercase and <m> if the letter is uppercase.

Press <x> or <m> to begin listening!

This concludes the story. Thank you for listening.

You will now answer some questions about the content of the story.
What were the astronaut candidates trained to do at the naval air station?
responses: {"Q0":"Eject out of aircraft and survive in water long enough to be rescued"}

stimulus: What gave the narrator his greatest feeling of accomplishment?

Thank you for your responses.

You will now answer some demographic, hearing, and general health questions.
How would you describe your musical skills/experiences?
How would you describe your general hearing abilities?

When you talk with someone at a place that strongly reverberates/echoes (e.g., in a church or train station),
can you understand what the person says?
When you are with a group (~5 people) in a lively restaurant, can you follow the group's conversation?
Based on the sound of a bus or truck, can you tell whether it is moving towards or away from you?
When you are in an unknown environment, can you tell from which direction a brief sound originates?
Are you able to ignore distracting sounds when you concentrate on a specific aspect of your acoustic surrounding?
